<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Australia to Block
   Offer by Maxwell
   For Newspapers
   ----
   By S. Karene Witcher
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST A.BLL A.BON U.MXC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   SYDNEY -- The Australian government again threw cold water
on Robert Maxwell's hopes of gaining a foothold in the
country's newspaper business.
   Treasurer Paul Keating, who has the last word on foreign
investment bids, said Canberra will block the British media
magnate's proposal to take a 49% stake in the daily West
Australian in Perth and other newspaper interests now
controlled by Alan Bond's Bell Group Ltd.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Speaking at a news conference in London, Mr. Keating said,
"We always have a restrictive view of newspaper ownership,
particularly capital-city newspapers. A 49% interest from a
shareholder that strong is a controlling interest, and we
would not agree to it."
   Mr. Keating defined a controlling interest as anything
above 25%, but he wouldn't say how much of a holding by Mr.
Maxwell would be tolerated. Australia now limits total
foreign ownership in television and radio stations to 20%,
though it has no firm guidelines for newspapers.
   The treasurer added that the needs of the debt-burdened
Mr. Bond, who is jettisoning assets in an effort to rescue
his Australian-based empire from collapse, are "a side issue"
to the country's larger interests.
   In London, Mr. Maxwell said it was "injudicious" of Mr.
Keating to comment before receiving an official application.
   Mr. Maxwell's Mirror Group PLC and Bell Group announced
that the British publisher had agreed to buy 49% of Bell
Group's publishing interests for 175 million Australian
dollars (US$135.1 million) in cash and assumption of A$75
million of debt.
   The price Mirror Group agreed to pay for just less than
half of the publishing interests effectively values the total
assets at about A$500 million -- much more than some analysts
think they're worth. "It seems to be a very high price," said
Robin Forbes, of Perth stock-brokerage firm Hartley Poynton
Ltd. Mr. Aspinall, however, called the price "very fair."
   Mirror Group's move follows Mr. Maxwell's purchase in
April, on his own behalf, of 14.9% of Bell Group. Australian
regulators have petitioned the courts to unwind that
transaction. The seller of the shares, David Aspinall, Bell
Group's managing director, has been accused of violating
corporate-takeover rules in the deal.
   As part of yesterday's offer, Mr. Maxwell agreed to help
fund a proposed buy-back -- most likely at a deep discount to
face value -- of some A$550 million of bonds convertible into
shares of Bell Group that are issued in Europe.
   Bell Group also owes bank lenders about A$260 million, Mr.
Aspinall said. If the proposed sale were completed, some of
the proceeds would likely be used to reduce Bell Group's bank
debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900612-0118
</DOCNO>
