<HL>
   International:
   Nationalization Is Sought
   For French Nuclear Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP F.FRM F.CGE F.DUM F.CLC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARIS -- French President Francois Mitterrand has approved
a plan under which French government-owned concerns will try
to take majority control of Framatome S.A., effectively
nationalizing France's nuclear power-plant builder,
presidential aides said.
   The decision reflects the continued willingness of
France's Socialist-led government to get involved in
industrial disputes when it believes the national interest is
at stake. In this case, France is more than 70%-dependent on
nuclear power for its electricity, the highest dependence
rate in the world. The government wants to ensure it controls
the main decisions at Framatome.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If the nationalization plan works, it would foil a plan by
France's large private-sector maker of electrical machinery,
telephone equipment and trains, Cie. Generale d'Electricite,
which holds 40% of Framatome, to gain majority control. CGE
said in March it intended to buy the 12% held by the
construction company Dumez S.A., on which CGE has first
refusal rights. The president seeks to block that. Until now,
the government considered Framatome's holdings balanced. The
state holds 45%, personnel the remaining 3%. Officials fear
that CGE's purchase plan would disrupt that balance.
   The president's plan calls for government-owned concerns,
possibly including the bank Credit Lyonnais and the nuclear
fuel-processing concern Cogema S.A., to wind up with about
51%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900612-0114
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900612-0114.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S., Canada Unions Set
   Telecommunications Pact
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- The two unions representing Canadian and U.S.
telecommunications industry workers said they concluded an
alliance that will allow them to support each other's
organizing, collective bargaining and research activities.
   Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of
America, and Fred Pomeroy, president of the Communications
and Electrical Workers of Canada, said the agreement -- the
first of its kind -- is essential in negotiating with the
multinational corporations that dominate the industry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We've got to deliver the message that a company cannot
practice good labor relations in one place and be anti-union
in another," Mr. Bahr said.
   He said the new alliance would allow the 700,000-member
CWA and the CWC, which represents 40,000 employees, to work
together in organizing employees of one company in both
countries.
   The union leaders said they expect the alliance to
strengthen their bargaining clout with multinational
corporations.
   A spokesman for Mississauga, Ontario-based Northern
Telecom Ltd., one of the large telecommunications companies
with operations in both the U.S. and Canada, said the
formation of the alliance "isn't surprising" given the degree
of globalization of the industry. But he declined further
comment until the company has had an opportunity to discuss
the move with union representatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
