<HL>
   British Rights Issue Shows SEC
   Ready to Ease Way for Foreigners
   ----
   By Michael R. Sesit and Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   ATTWY U.WSG FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is close to taking
yet another step to make it easier for foreign companies to
sell securities in the U.S.
   The SEC's willingness to relax strict U.S. registration
guidelines for foreign issuers was signaled in an
announcement Friday by Attwoods PLC. The British
waste-management company said that it planned an #82 million
($138 million) rights offering that will be registered with
the SEC. The offering gives shareholders the right to
purchase one new share at 390 pence for each four ordinary
shares they hold.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   S.G. Warburg &amp; Co., the lead underwriter, says it believes
this will be the first underwritten rights issue for a
British company to be registered with the SEC.
   In the past, foreign companies often steered clear of
registering securities offerings in the U.S., either because
they had too few U.S. shareholders to make the expense
worthwhile or because the detailed filings were considered a
hassle. The result was that U.S. investors were forced to
sell their unexercised rights and denied the opportunity to
participate fully in the transaction.
   But because the SEC is likely to bend U.S. rules,
Attwoods' U.S. shareholders are expected to be able to take
full advantage of the company's rights offering.
   The SEC hasn't formally approved the Attwoods application,
but is expected to shortly.
   The expected Attwoods offering would be the latest in a
string of measures taken recently by the SEC to accommodate
foreign corporations that wish to raise money in the U.S.
stock and bond markets.
   Part of the impetus behind the SEC's new stance is the
planned 1992 abolition of trade and investment barriers in
the 12 countries that comprise the European Community,
something that will enhance Europe's position as a financial
power.
   The SEC, led by Chairman Richard Breeden, is acutely aware
that international capital markets have grown far more
interdependent in the past decade. To keep the U.S. as the
world's premier capital market, the agency feels it must
adjust to investor and issuer needs.
   The SEC's most wide-reaching step came earlier this
spring, when it created an easy way for foreign companies to
sell debt and stock to large U.S. institutions like pension
funds and insurance companies. That provision, called Rule
144a, is designed to help encourage European and Asian
companies to raise funds in the U.S. private placement
market. At the same time, it allows large U.S. investors
expanded investment opportunities.
   "If there are good opportunities for American investors
abroad, Americans should be allowed to take advantage of
those," said Marianne Smythe, executive assistant to the SEC
chairman. At the same time, "For American businesses to raise
capital, it is useful for them to have access to investors
other than those in the U.S. That reduces the cost of
capital."
   With about 20% of its stock outstanding held in the U.S.
and roughly 70% of its business there, "Attwoods was eager to
insure that its U.S. shareholders were able to participate in
the issue on the same terms as their non-U.S. shareholders,"
says Lucas J. Wilson, a vice president at Warburg's U.S. unit
in New York.
   Specifically, the SEC has signaled that it is willing to
speed up Attwoods's registration to save the company from
what can be higher costs, says Warburg. The agency is also
expected to exempt partially the securities firm from Rule
10b6, which effectively bans an underwriter from making a
market in an issue during the offering period. (A
market-maker commits to buy and sell shares and smooth market
imbalances.) To comply, Warburg would have to cease making a
market for Attwoods shares in London.
   Instead, the British brokerage house says that the SEC
will allow the firm to actively trade Attwoods stock in
Britain until five days before the offer's termination date,
July 24. The SEC will also mandate that if the share price is
trading at less than 110% of the rights exercise price, or
390 pence, Warburg can only make a market on a passive basis,
in which it can't actively solicit business. The firm won't
be allowed to make a market in the U.S. during the offering
period.
   The SEC said it had only received the Attwoods filing last
Friday and was still reviewing it.
   Making a market in London is important to both Attwoods
and Warburg. The broker claims it is the largest of the three
or four major firms that make a market in Attwoods shares,
and that to exclude it from Attwoods transactions could
hinder trading in Attwoods shares and the success of the
rights issue. In addition, the International Stock Exchange
in London could penalize the firm for failing to back its
commitment to maintain a market in the stock.
   "The message from the SEC is that it's easier than it was
before for foreign companies to operate in the U.S. capital
markets," says Warburg's Mr. Wilson. "The SEC's attitude here
is that it isn't that complicated, it can be done, and that
if Attwoods can do it, so can other companies.
   Linda Quinn, the SEC's director of corporation finance,
said the agency is acutely concerned that the SEC's timing
schedule not deter foreign companies from making rights
offerings available to U.S. investors. "We've tried to
accommodate timing practices by putting in a lot of extra
effort," she said. "If we have to review documents around the
clock, that's what we'll do."
   The Attwoods offering price represents an 18% discount to
what Attwoods stock was selling for at the time. Yesterday,
Attwoods closed unchanged at 476 pence. The company's
American depositary receipts, each of which represents five
Attwoods shares, rose 37.5 cents to close at $41.125.
   Still, the agency remains concerned about moving too
quickly and pulling back on some of the customer protections
that have been the cornerstone of SEC policy since the 1930s.
"We're doing what's appropriate to assist in the process of
furthering international flows of capital," the SEC's Ms.
Smythe said. But, "none of us want that to be done at the
expense of regulations necessary to assure reasonable
safety."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900612-0099
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900612-0099.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Advertising:
   Decline of Tobacco Sales
   In Canada Fuels Ad Debate
   ----
   By Joanne Lipman
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA TAXES EUROP FREST HNZ OMCM WNEWS SAA U.LIG
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
HOUSEHOLD AND PERSONAL-CARE PRODUCTS (HHP)
</IN>
<LP>
   Do tobacco ad bans work? Tobacco companies have always
insisted they don't, that tobacco ads don't make anyone start
smoking in the first place. But Canada's 18-month-old tobacco
ad ban suggests otherwise, and could help tobacco opponents
in their fight to block the ads in the U.S.
   Since Canada instituted the ban in January 1989, tobacco
consumption, which had been declining, has slipped at an even
steeper rate. Since 1982, tobacco sales have fallen off 25%,
with the steepest annual decline, nearly 7%, coming last year
along with the ban. And the drop seems to be getting faster,
with sales in the first four months of this year plunging by
10%, according to tobacco executives and government
officials.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   To the ban's proponents, those figures are clear evidence
that the ad ban is making its mark. "Smoking is a tough nut
to crack, and we didn't think this was going to make it go
away overnight, but certainly all the signs are in the right
direction," says Byron Rogers, an analyst with the tobacco
products section of Canada's Department of National Health
and Welfare in Ottawa.
   Tobacco companies insist that advertising has nothing to
do with the consumption decline. They blame big tax increases
on cigarettes put in place at the same time as the ban. A
pack of smokes in Canada now costs as much as C$5 (US$4.25),
more than a dollar more than before the ban, and double the
price just south of the border in the U.S. "Obviously, it has
to do with taxes," says a spokesman for Imperial Tobacco
Ltd., Canada's largest tobacco company.
   Adds a spokeswoman for RJR Macdonald, a Canadian unit of
RJR Nabisco, "The minute the taxes increase, you can see the
decline in sales. It's such an instantaneous reaction, and
advertising doesn't work that way. Advertising is slow,
methodical and cumulative."
   The debate over tobacco advertising is being touched off
anew as other countries move to restrict the ads. France's
cabinet last week voted to ban all tobacco advertising
effective Jan. 1, 1993. Australia and New Zealand both have
proposed severe restrictions. Italy, Portugal and most of the
Scandinavian countries already bar tobacco ads from both
television and print media. In Canada, the ban is being
fought in the Quebec Superior Court in Montreal, where two of
the country's major tobacco companies have challenged its
constitutionality.
   The problem on both sides of the debate is that it is
virtually impossible to isolate tobacco advertising's impact.
Other factors are bound to get in the way, from taxes to
health education. In Canada, the problem is compounded
because the ban is being phased in gradually; there hasn't
been a clean break from tobacco ads. Billboards have been
reduced but won't be banned until year end. In-store
advertising won't be eliminated until 1993. Sports
sponsorships won't be affected at all.
   "I wouldn't expect a big impact of the advertising ban in
the short run," says Richard W. Pollay, professor of
marketing at the University of British Columbia in Vancouver.
"In the long run, it affects starting rates and quitting
rates, but that takes a new generation before you start to
see that."
   Mr. Pollay and other academics, though, believe that
tobacco ad bans are effective -- at least to some extent.
Jeffrey Harris, an economics professor at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, contends the tobacco companies'
argument that stiff taxes are to blame for declines just
doesn't wash. Mr. Harris, who studied ad bans in other
countries, says cigarette consumption typically declined
following ad bans and that "the declines were bigger than you
would expect from taxes alone. Tax increases alone couldn't
explain it in any country."
   The cigarette companies' other major argument is that they
use ads only to persuade current smokers to switch brands,
not to entice nonsmokers into a bad habit. "Advertising is
basically to attract those who already smoke from one brand
to another. It doesn't affect consumption," says a spokesman
for Rothmans Benson &amp; Hedges in Toronto.
   But Mr. Pollay, who studied cigarette company strategies
before testifying in favor of the ban, dismisses that
argument. "The corporate documents are point blank that
they're targeting youth and would-be quitters, what they call
prequitters," he says. "Most of the attention is to provide
reassurances to people who are anxious about their health,
and to induce starters -- because in the long run, that's the
name of the game."
   In Canada, if the ad ban survives the constitutional
challenge, the ultimate test of its effectiveness won't come
for another few years, when the country will be able to
measure whether fewer people start smoking. So far, the
results are inconclusive. About 20% of 15- to 19-year-old
Canadians are regular smokers, about the same percentage as
has been true since the mid-1980s, says the Department of
National Health's Mr. Rogers. "Ultimately, we would like to
see more success in affecting starting smokers," he says. "We
still have a problem."
   ---
