<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Time Off: Diversions and Excursions June 12-25
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<LP>
   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.: "Old Master
Drawings From the National Gallery of Scotland" -- Almost 90
drawings by Italian, Dutch and French artists such as
Raphael, Piranesi, Van Dyck, Rembrandt, Poussin and
Fragonard. Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue NW, June
24-Sept. 23. The show then travels to the Kimbell Art Museum
in Fort Worth, Texas, Nov. 3, 1990-Jan. 13, 1991.
                                                                                                       

   Museum of Science, Boston: "Soviet Space" -- More than 50
artifacts document the history of the Soviet space program,
its current status and its future direction. Highlights
include a full-scale model of Sputnik I, the first artificial
satellite to orbit the Earth; Lunakhod 2, a lunar roving
vehicle; components of Luna 24, the last unmanned probe to
visit the moon; and a model of the Mir space station. The
show was produced in cooperation with Glavkosmos, the Soviet
civilian space agency. Science Park. Through Sept. 23.
                                                                                                       

   DANCE
                                                                                                       

   Mark Morris: The provocative expatriate choreographer and
his Monnaie Dance Group give the home folks a chance to see
what they've been up to in Brussels on this summer mini-tour.
There'll be a different program at each stop. The Boston
engagement, at the Emerson Majestic Theater (219 Tremont St.,
617-492-7578) tonight-Sunday, offers his critically acclaimed
"Love Song Waltzes"; the dates at New York's Brooklyn Academy
of Music (30 Lafayette Ave., 718-636-4100), June 20-23,
feature Morris's interpretation of Purcell's opera "Dido and
Aeneas," with the choreographer dancing both the ill-fated
Carthaginian queen and her mortal enemy, the Sorceress. The
final stop, at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival (Route 20,
Becket, Mass., 413-243-0745) June 26-30, marks the U.S.
premiere of "Going Away Party."
                                                                                                       

   FESTIVAL
                                                                                                       

   JVC Jazz Festival: The annual Big Apple music marathon
opens June 22 with a blast -- concerts by trumpeters Miles
Davis and Dizzy Gillespie (Davis plays Avery Fisher Hall,
while Gillespie sounds off at Carnegie Hall). For the next
week, there'll be sounds to suit almost every jazz fan, at
sites throughout the metropolitan area. Highlights include
the dream double bill of Ray Charles and Roberta Flack (Avery
Fisher Hall, June 24); the reunion of Brazilian vocalist
Milton Nascimento and saxophonist Wayne Shorter (AFH, June
26); grande dame Ella Fitzgerald (AFH, June 29); a rare
collaboration among guitarist Pat Metheny, Herbie Hancock,
Jack DeJohnette and Dave Holland (Beacon Theatre, two shows,
June 30); and a "Knitting Factory Goes Uptown" series
spotlighting exciting young performers (Equitable Center, 787
Seventh Ave., 5 p.m. June 22-29). (212) 787-2020.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   Opera Theatre of Saint Louis offers a rarely performed
1899 Dvorak piece, "The Devil and Kate," about a Bohemian
princess who sets the peasants of her realm free. Richard
Buckley conducts and the cast includes Joseph Evans as Jirka
the shepard, Phyllis Pancella as the village girl Kate, and
Alexandra Coku as the princess. June 14, 16, 20, 22 and 24.
Also on the card for the season, which ends June 24, are a
Colin Graham staging of Britten's "Peter Grimes" (June 16 and
23), Donizetti's "The Daughter of the Regiment" (June 13, 15,
19 and 21) and Mozart's "The Marriage of Figaro" (June 12, 17
and 23). Loretto-Hilton Center, 130 Edgar Road (at Big Bend)
on the campus of Webster University. (314) 961-0644.
                                                                                                       

   Johnny Clegg &amp; Savuka: For the past decade this "white
Zulu" and his multiracial ensembles have beaten the drum for
freedom in South Africa. Currently, he's on tour as the
opening act for Tracy Chapman, providing frenetic Zulu
dancing and songs from his new album "Cruel, Crazy, Beautiful
World" (Atlantic). Dates include: Clarkston, Mich. (Pine Knob
Theater), June 15; Cuyahoga Falls, Ohio (Blossom Music
Theater), June 16; Atlanta (Lakewood Amphitheater), June 19;
Pittsburgh (Star Lake Amphitheater), June 22; Holmdel, N.J.
(Garden State Arts Center), June 23; Philadelphia (Mann Music
Center), June 24; New York (Beacon Theatre), June 26;
Wantagh, N.Y. (Jones Beach Theater), June 28; Manchester,
N.H. (Veteran's Memorial Park), June 30; Lenox, Mass.
(Tanglewood), July 2.
