<HL>
   Microsoft, Everex File
   Suit Against Alleged
   Product Counterfeiters
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   MSFT EVRX
</CO>
<IN>
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   REDMOND, Wash. -- Microsoft Corp. said it and Everex
Systems Inc. together filed suit against 16 individuals and
companies, accusing them of producing and distributing
counterfeit copies of a Microsoft computer product.
   Microsoft, a software company, and Everex, a Microsoft
licensee, alleged that the group sold some 30,000 fake MS-DOS
operating systems under Everex's ParCorp. label. An operating
system controls the basic functions of a computer. Everex has
a licensing agreement with Microsoft under which it produces
and markets the MS-DOS operating system under the ParCorp.
trade name.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Microsoft sells more than 10 million MS-DOS products a
year.
   Microsoft said the 16 defendants include J&amp;S International
Co. of San Jose, Calif.; Benny S. Lee, Norman Chan and Susan
Chan, all of Fremont, Calif.; and Micro-Generation, a
division of Continental Technolgoy Inc., located in Edison,
N.J. None could be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
