<HL>
   Business Brief -- General Motors Corp.:
   Hughes Air Unit Suspension
   Is Removed by Air Force
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   GM GMH
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   Hughes Aircraft Co. said the Air Force removed its
suspension that had temporarily barred certain operations of
Hughes missile-systems group from receiving new government
contracts.
   The Air Force suspended the company last month in the wake
of Hughes's guilty plea to charges of improperly using two
classified Pentagon budget-planning documents in 1984.
Hughes, a unit of General Motors Corp., agreed to pay $3.6
million in criminal and civil penalties as part of the plea
agreement.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The temporary suspension, which covered engineering,
research and certain other operations at the Canoga Park,
Calif., facility of the company's missile-making group, was
in effect while the Air Force reviewed Hughes plan to
re-establish itself as a "responsible contractor."
   The Air Force's decision came despite assertions by
prosecutors that Hughes officials went to greater lengths
than those at almost any other company to carry out the
document-swapping scheme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900612-0011
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900612-0011.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Furniture Industry
   Figures Are Sentenced
   On Fraud Charges
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A federal judge sentenced three retail
furniture businessmen on fraud and conspiracy charges in
connection with a scheme that defrauded investors of $52
million.
   Louis Bigman, 65 years old, of Douglaston, N.Y., was
sentenced to 46 months in prison. Ben Wernikoff, 64, of
Jericho, N.Y., and Henry Switsky, 61, of Marlboro, N.J., were
each sentenced to 37 months. The three men pleaded guilty in
federal court in Manhattan in January.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The defendants were charged with defrauding investors
through the sale of retail installment-loan agreements from
Alcor Trading Corp. and Marba Furniture Inc., two furniture
companies owned by Messrs. Bigman, Wernikoff and Switsky. The
investors were told that their money would be used to buy the
loan agreements at a sharp discount and that they would make
a profit of 15% to 22% when the defendants collected the full
amounts due under the installment loans.
   Instead, according to the U.S. attorney's office in
Manhattan, the money was used to pay off earlier investors in
the scheme or to make unsecured loans -- which weren't repaid
-- to other companies owned by the defendants. The scheme
fell apart in March 1989 when Alcor and another company owned
by the defendants were placed in bankruptcy-law proceedings,
partly because investors sought the return of their money.
   Although the defendants have agreed to try to make
restitution, the defrauded investors are expected to be
repaid less than 1% of the total owed to them, prosecutors
said.
   Another defendant, Ira Goldstein, pleaded guilty to
conspiracy and will be sentenced Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900612-0010
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900612-0010.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Meret to Go Private
   Through Stock Split
</HL>
<DATE>
06/12/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MRET
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio -- Meret Inc. said it plans a reverse stock
split that will transform the retail consulting and design
concern into a privately held company.
   Under the plan, each 2,500 existing shares would be
converted to one new share. Holders owning fewer than 2,500
shares, or a number not divisible by 2,500, would receive 30
cents a share in cash for each current share that otherwise
would become a fractional share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company has 10.2 million shares outstanding, owned by
about 1,600 shareholders. Officers and directors control 46%
of the stock.
   In over-the-counter trading yesterday, Meret shares closed
at 25 cents bid, unchanged.
   The goal of the plan is to reduce the number of
shareholders to less than 300, which would allow Meret to
terminate its registration with the Securities and Exchange
Commission and no longer be a public company, Meret said. For
the company, with annual revenue of slightly more than $10
million, the expense and management time required to meet SEC
regulations for public companies is disproportionate to
benefits obtained, Meret said.
   Meret retained Harmon Group, a Columbus investment banking
firm, to give an opinion on the fairness of the plan.
Shareholders will be asked to approve the plan at a special
meeting later this summer, the company said.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   HARMAN GROUP is a Columbus, Ohio, investment banking
company. The company's name was misstated in Tuesday's
edition.
   (WSJ June 14, 1990)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
